cron jobs and one Telegram group still running — the main session and Lead direct are both done. Now I'm calculating how long each has been going: the DTLX cron started around 19 hours ago, the QLHV cron about 2 hours 53 minutes back, and the QLHV group roughly 6 hours 22 minutes ago.\n\nThere's also a status update cron job that's been running for just a minute or so. I'm realizing I need to be more careful with my timestamp conversions though — let me verify the math on these start times against the current time of 1776182810. 493 = 1776182810493 ms (Tue Apr 14 16:06:50 UTC)\n\n1. `cron:e7885813` — started at 1776182809936 = ~14 seconds ago (it's this cron session itself!)\n2. `cron:6f3323ef` — started at 1776152701090\n   - 1776182810493 - 1776152701090 = 30109403 ms ≈ 30109 seconds ≈ 8h 21m 49s\n   - Let me double-check: 1776182810 - 1776152701 = 30109 seconds\n   - 30109 / 3600 = 8.36 hours ≈ 8h 21m\n   - But the last message was at 1776182690124, so I need to recalculate from there instead — that gives me about 19 hours since the session started.\n\nNow I'm looking at the next two sessions: the first one started at 1776180724499 and has been running for roughly 2 hours based on the timestamp difference, while the QLHV group session began at 1776163408296 and is still active with a recent message from 1776178681406. Now I'm calculating the durations more carefully by checking the last message timestamps from the cron sessions themselves, which gives me an accurate picture of how long each task has been running based on their most recent activity rather than just their start times. I'm working through the timestamp conversions more carefully—1776182810 milliseconds translates to 1776182 seconds from the Unix epoch, which puts us at around April 14, 2026 in UTC. Let me verify this against known date calculations to get the exact time down to the hour. Looking at the last message timestamps, the DTLX cron session is about 2 hours old, the QLHV cron is running at 45 minutes, and the QLHV group is active at roughly 3 hours 40 minutes.\n\nNow I'm formatting the report for the 16:06 UTC timestamp on April 14th. I need to clarify the session naming convention — the cron job identifiers like `cron:e7885813` are actually labels that appear in session metadata, while the longer UUID strings are the actual session keys stored in the system. I'm realizing the core issue is that my own session appears in the list with `running` status, but I need to exclude it from my report to avoid a self-referential loop. The challenge is that the list results don't clearly identify which entry is my current session, so I need to filter based on the session key pattern and timestamps to exclude it properly. I should send the report using just the session key without the agent prefix since the system will route it correctly to the target session. The main question now is whether to include that current cron session in the count or exclude it—I think the latter makes sense since it would just be reporting on itself, which isn't useful.\n\nLooking at the other sessions, I can see the DTLX cron is running and handling 5-minute progress monitoring, though it's been active for about 2 hours which seems longer than expected, but that makes sense if it's a persistent session that wakes up periodically. Now I need to figure out how to reference this cron session itself when compiling the full report.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the format expects all sessions in the report to be ones I'm reporting on, not including my own cron session. So I should exclude myself and just report on the other four active sessions. Let me send the report to the Telegram lead now."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_urmeidw33c7z_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134","message":"🌐 Orbis — Agent Status | 16:06 UTC 14 Apr\n\nActive sessions: 4\n• cron:6f3323ef (5p DTLX): running — 5-min progress monitoring (DTL